        <h1><marquee behavior="alternate";bgcolor="yellow";height="1000" >Dosa with Coconut Chutney</marquee></h1>
    </header>

    <section>
        <h2>Dosa Ingredients</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>2 cups dosa rice</li>
            <li>1/2 cup urad dal (black gram)</li>
            <li>1/4 teaspoon fenugreek seeds</li>
            <li>Salt to taste</li>
            <li>Oil or ghee for cooking</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Chutney Ingredients</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>1 cup grated coconut</li>
            <li>2 green chilies</li>
            <li>1/2 inch ginger</li>
            <li>1 tablespoon roasted chana dal (split gram)</li>
            <li>A small bunch of cilantro</li>
            <li>Salt to taste</li>
            <li>Water as needed</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2> Tags</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>breakfast</li>
            <li>indian</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Instructions</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Wash dosa rice, urad dal, and fenugreek seeds separately. Soak them in water for 4-6 hours.</li>
            <li>Grind the soaked urad dal and fenugreek seeds together to a smooth batter. Transfer to a large bowl.</li>
            <li>Grind the soaked dosa rice to a slightly coarse texture. Mix it with the urad dal batter in the bowl. Add salt and mix well. Allow it to ferment overnight or for at least 8 hours.</li>
            <li>For the chutney, blend grated coconut, green chilies, ginger, roasted chana dal, cilantro, and salt with enough water to make a smooth paste.</li>
            <li>Heat a dosa griddle or non-stick pan. Pour a ladle of dosa batter in the center and spread it in a circular motion to form a thin dosa. Drizzle oil or ghee on the edges.</li>
            <li>Cook until the dosa turns golden brown on the bottom. Flip and cook the other side briefly if desired.</li>
            <li>Serve hot dosas with the coconut chutney.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

